1. Introduction¶

1.1 Motivation:
    Happiness appears to be an increasingly important factor to our existence. People have begun to embrace being happy as a concept in it of itself. As we begin to optimize and desire more of this intangible qualia, we as a species have begun to categorize and break "happiness" down into what appears to be relevant components in a desire to further our understanding. While there are many individualistic things one can do to improve their happiness such as practicing meditation and gratefulness, and a whole host of new research and media centered around happiness, this tutorial will attempt to examine larger nation-wide factors that can impact happiness.

1.2 Libraries Used:
    Pandas: used to represent and see data in dataframes
    Matplotlib: used generate data plots
    SKLearn: used to analyze data and predict factors
    Numpy: used to support data and pandas
    Statistics: more generalized statistical methods
    Scipy: used for some statistical analysis
    Statsmodels: used for additional statistical analysis
    Seaborn: used for additional data visualization
    Folium + Requests: used for mapping

The data from Kaggle is kind enough to provide a quick-preview. It appears that each year's data set is non-homogenous. Let's try to get them all uniform for more easy comparisons. The more recent data from 2018/2019 formats seem to be more concise and make more sense than previous years. Extraneous data will be ignored and there will be a focus on GDP, Social Support, Life Expectancy, Freedom, Generosity, and Perception of Governmental Corruption.

To give a quick explanation of the data:

  1. Overall Rank: of the countries surveyed, which has the highest happiness score, and therefore, its happiness rank
  2. Country or Region: self-explanatory, which country was surveyed
  3. GDP per capita: a relative scaled measurement of the economic might of the country per person (how much "stuff" a country outputs relative to its population)
  4. Social Support: a relative scaled measurement of how much the people surveyed felt supported by family and friends
  5. Healthy Life Expectancy: a relative scaled measurement of the average life expectancy of an individual (from natural causes, excluding accidents etc.)
  6. Freedom to Make Life Choices: a relative scaled measurement of ability to decide things in life
  7. Generosity: a relative scaled measurement of how generous people are (with donations and such)
  8. Perceptions of Corruption: a relative scaled measurement of how corrupt people think their government is

Now that we have the data normalized, let us begin looking for discernible patterns. Let's create a heatmap of the dataframes to see if anything obvious appears.

4. Data Analysis and Visualization¶

In [14]:
Years = [2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]
dataframes = [data_15, data_16, data_17, data_18, data_19]

for i,y in zip(dataframes, Years):
    correlation = i.corr()
    sn.heatmap(correlation, annot = True)
    plt.title(y)
    plt.show()

From the heatmaps indicating correlation, it's quite clear that most things have a positive correlation with regards to the Happiness Score. Not surprisingly, GDP per capita, social support, life expectancy, freedom, and perception of lower governmental corruption are all correlated with feeling happy. What is surprising is generosity has the least correlation with happiness of all the other factors and is GDP agnostic-as in everyone has similar levels of generosity. GDP per capita, Social Support, and Healthy Life Expectancy all look very similar w.r.t. correlation to Happiness Score though.

Unsurprisingly based on the maps, the happiest countries are typically "developed" (such as western Europe and America etc.) and the unhappy countries are "underdeveloped" (e.g. parts of Africa). The happier countries typically have a strong GDP as well as relatively more advanced technology and healthcare etc. The unhappy countries typically have weak economies, poor healthcare, and have other societal factors at play such as war, exploitation, strong religious states etc.

Let's average out the 5 years of data (only taking into consideration countries that were surveyed over 5 years) to somewhat account for single-year aberrations.

def avg(x):
    return sum(x)/len(x)
In [28]:
dataframes = [data_15, data_16, data_17, data_18, data_19]

for country in intersection:
    ranks, scores, GDPs, socials, LEs, freedoms, gen, perceptions = ([] for i in range(8))
    for dataframe in dataframes:
        ranks.append(int(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Overall Rank']))
        scores.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Score']))
        GDPs.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['GDP per capita']))
        socials.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Social Support']))
        LEs.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Healthy Life Expectancy']))
        freedoms.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Freedom to Make Life Choices']))
        gen.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Generosity']))
        perceptions.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Perceptions of Corruption']))
    

    Avg_Rank = avg(ranks)
    Avg_Score = avg(scores)
    Avg_GDP = avg(GDPs)
    Avg_Social = avg(socials)
    Avg_LE = avg(LEs)
    Avg_Freedom = avg(freedoms)
    Avg_Generosity = avg(gen)
    Avg_Perceptions = avg(perceptions)
    
    to_add = pd.DataFrame([[Avg_Rank, country, Avg_Score, Avg_GDP, Avg_Social, Avg_LE, Avg_Freedom, Avg_Generosity, Avg_Perceptions]],
                          columns = ['Overall Rank', 'Country or Region', 'Score', 'GDP per capita', 'Social Support', 'Healthy Life Expectancy', 
                                     'Freedom to Make Life Choices', 'Generosity', 'Perceptions of Corruption'])
    merged = merged.append(to_add, ignore_index=True)

5. Hypothesis testing and machine learning¶

Taking a closer look at the heat map generated above we can quickly notice that GDP per capita, social support, and healthy life expectancy have extremely high correlations with happiness score. This suggests that these variables might be correlated to each other.

The correlation between GDP per capita, social support, and healthy life expectancy are extremely high.

This presents an issue in creating a multi-variable linear regression model. Since the predictor variables are highly correlated the precision of estimated regression coefficient decreases. By using highly correlated predictors in a regression model we are effectively increasing the standard error and overfitting our model to our data set. Thus we will examine some linear regression models and apply the most effective model to out data set.

First we apply a multi-variable linear regression model with the predicto variables: GDP per Capita, Healthy Life Expectancy and Social Support.

In [34]:
X = merged[['GDP per capita', 'Healthy Life Expectancy', 'Social Support']]
y = merged['Score']

regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
regr.fit(X,y)

mod = sm.OLS(y,X)
model_fit = mod.fit()
print(model_fit.summary())

Examining this model we find that the Adjusted R-Squared value is extremely high, which means that this model fits our data very well. However, as we further examine the model we run into some issues. As we predicted above, the model is over fitting our data. Examining the P values we find that the p-value for GDP per capita is extremely high (.321) and our standard error across the three variables are also very high. The high correlation between the three predictor variables is fitting our data extremely well, which makes for a useless predictior.

Since using the three variables was not effective in generating a good model, we will examine the past table and attempt to generate a model that is more effective in predicting overall happiness. The heat map above showed that Healthy life Expectancy and social support had the lowest correlation, so lets analyze this as a model:

Once again, we can clearly see that the model fits our data extremely well with an adjusted R-squared value of .984. However, the standad errors are extremely high. This indicates that our model does not perform well as a predictor.

From the above trials, we notice that the correlation between the variables is way too high and causing a lot of interaction between each other and negatively affecting our model. We will now take a look at a regression model using only the predictor variable GDP Per Capita since it had the highest correlation to happiness score.

The inclusion of these two variables increased the adjusted R-squared of the model. However this improvement of R-squared is not worth the additional standard error that we receive from the inclusion of these two variables. The standard error for the two additional variables are .57 and .66, which are way too high. They also cause the standard error of GDP per capita to increase to .194. This model fails to be a good predictor, and overfits our dataset.

Overall we found that the best linear regression model for predicting Happiness score is Score Vs. GDP Per Capita. This model yields a very high R-squared value at a very small standard error. This actually makes perfect sense, GDP Per Capita is highly correlated to most of the other variables. Developed countries tend to have the highest GDP which in turn cause a lower perception of corruption, higher life expectancy... All of the other variables are highly correlated to GDP Per Capita. Using highly correlated variables introduce a significant amount of error to the model, since we don't know how much of the change in the model is truly attributed to change of GDP per capita.

4.5 Food for Thought¶

Previously, GDP, Social Support, and Life Expectancy were all very close in correlation to happiness score, and it was difficult to differentiate them. While still close, GDP per capita slightly edges the other two out and is likely the strongest factor in determining happiness for a nation.

While this is interesting, looking at how a nation's happiness can change seems very prudent given society's currrent chase of "happiness". It can give a better sense of how sensitive happiness can be to the factors polled. Let's look at nations who have changed in ranking between 2015 and 2019.

In [40]:
intersection = list(set(data_15['Country or Region']) & set(data_19['Country or Region']))
#Will define difference as 2019 ranking - 2015 ranking
In [41]:
differences = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Rank Difference', 'Country or Region', 'Score Diff', 'GDP Diff', 'Social Diff', 'LE Diff', 
                 'Freedom Diff', 'Generosity Diff', 'Corruption Diff'])

for country in intersection:
    rank_diff = int(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Overall Rank']) - int(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Overall Rank'])
    score_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Score']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Score'])
    gdp_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'GDP per capita']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'GDP per capita'])
    social_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Social Support']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Social Support'])
    le_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Healthy Life Expectancy']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Healthy Life Expectancy'])
    freedom_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Freedom to Make Life Choices']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Freedom to Make Life Choices'])
    gen_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Generosity']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Generosity'])
    corruption_diff = float(data_19.loc[data_19['Country or Region'] == country, 'Perceptions of Corruption']) - float(data_15.loc[data_15['Country or Region'] == country, 'Perceptions of Corruption'])
    
    to_add = pd.DataFrame([[rank_diff, country, score_diff, gdp_diff, social_diff, le_diff, freedom_diff, gen_diff, corruption_diff]],
                          columns = ['Rank Difference', 'Country or Region', 'Score Diff', 'GDP Diff', 'Social Diff', 'LE Diff', 
                                     'Freedom Diff', 'Generosity Diff', 'Corruption Diff'])
    differences = differences.append(to_add, ignore_index=True)

Looking at how drastically some countries changed ranks, let's see how the variable correlation for countries that increased in happiness, and those that decreased in happiness differ.

In [51]:
#remember this is using rank difference, 2019-2015 rank. 
positive = differences[differences['Rank Difference'] >= 0]
correlation = positive.corr()
sn.heatmap(correlation, annot = True)
plt.title("Decreases in Happiness Rank")
plt.show()

This is quite different to the initial heatmaps generated. This would indicate that the strongest factors that despite increases in GDP, Social Support, and Freedom are correlated with DECREASES in happiness. Life Expectancy bucked the trend of the 3 previously enterwtined variables (GDP, social, life expectancy) and actually increased despite happiness decreasing. This could maybe be explained by technology advancing or modern healthcare being more prevalent/expanded throughout the world (e.g. Bill Gates fighting malaria). While these things should probably be further examined, this tutorial simply lacks the data to make any stronger, more meaningful analysis.

In [52]:
negative = differences[differences['Rank Difference'] <= 0]
correlation = negative.corr()
sn.heatmap(correlation, annot = True)
plt.title("Increases in Happiness")
plt.show()

This heatmap should indicate factors for countries that are now MORE happy. Again, it seems to tell a different tale than the initial heatmaps. This would indicate that countries that became happier gained some GDP, but the stronger predictors for becoming more happy is decreases in perceived corruption, and increases in generosity. Obviously more money is always helpful, but larger systemic changes like decreases in corruption led to more happiness gains. This could maybe be explained by the countries did already have a requisite amount of wealth and other factors, and instead individuals needed to begin cultivating their own happiness. It's difficult to gain anything more meaningful, but this could warrant further exploration.

6. Conclusions¶

We set out on this tutorial to hopefully gain a better understanding of happiness and factors that can influence it at a societal level. Several main factors were examined: GDP, social support, life expectancy, freedom, generosity, and perceived governmental corruption. Most things however, are related to GDP (or it can easily be intuited WHY GDP has all of these things linked) which made analysis at times difficult. The one outlier is generosity where that appeared to be GDP-agnostic. Happier regions "just happened" to be more technologically advanced "first-world countries" and less happy countries are less developed. This isn't news to anybody. However, it still has merit to examine which countries are happy explicitly to see if there's things that can be used to increase a nation's happiness at a systematic level. Furthermore when looking at countries that increased or decreased in happiness over 5 years, many more interesting things were revealed. There was a clear trend of money decidedly NOT buying happiness, as in countries gained significant GDP per capita but had decreases to happiness. Countries that gained happiness saw strong correlation to decreases in perceived corruption and increases in generosity. 

While it would be great to have any simple fixes (even country-wide fixes), it's quite clear that happiness is a difficult topic to examine given its qualia-like existence. We would like to humbly present a list of TED talks on the subject: https://www.ted.com/playlists/4/what_makes_you_happy and recommend The Happiness Lab with Dr. Laurie Santos for individuals and recommend meditation and gratefulness practice.
